I've identified the cause of the HTTP 431 error! After modifying the middleware.ts file to remove "/account" from the protected routes (as you suggested), the account page now loads correctly and shows the sign-in form. The issue was a redirect loop: 1. The middleware was protecting the /account route 2. But /account is also set as the sign-in page in NextAuth 3. So unauthorized users were caught in an infinite redirect loop between middleware and NextAuth, eventually leading to the HTTP 431 error I've committed this change to GitHub as a diagnostic fix, but I understand this is just for testing purposes. What do you recommend as the proper solution? Should we: 1. Keep /account unprotected and only protect pages within the account section? 2. Use a different route for the sign-in page (not /account)? 3. Implement a different approach to route protection? Looking forward to your guidance on implementing a permanent fix.
15:13
That's fantastic news! Excellent work pinpointing the redirect loop as the cause of the HTTP 431 error. Your diagnosis was spot on.
Regarding the proper solution, you've outlined the common approaches. I recommend Option 1: Keep /account unprotected and only protect specific pages within the account section (like /account/edit-profile, /account/itineraries, etc.).
This is a clean and common pattern. The /account page itself will act as the entry point. If a user is not authenticated, it will display the sign-in form (as NextAuth is configured to use it as the signIn page). If the user is authenticated, the /account/page.tsx component can then display their account overview or dashboard.
Here’s how you can implement this permanent fix:
  1. Adjust middleware.ts: Modify your protectedRoutes array in middleware.ts to specifically list the sub-routes that require authentication, leaving /account itself out of this list if it's purely serving as the sign-in page for unauthenticated users or a general lander for authenticated users.
    For example:
    typescript
    // src/middleware.ts
// ... other imports

export async function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const token = await getToken({ req, secret: process.env.NEXTAUTH_SECRET });
  const { pathname } = req.nextUrl;

  // Define protected routes that require authentication
  // /account itself is the sign-in page, so it shouldn't be protected by this logic if unauthenticated
  // users need to see a login form there.
  const protectedRoutes = [
    "/account/edit-profile",
    "/account/itineraries", // Add other specific account sub-pages here
    // Add other routes like "/checkout" or "/my-bookings" if they exist and need protection
  ];

  const isProtectedRoute = protectedRoutes.some(route => pathname.startsWith(route));

  if (isProtectedRoute && !token) {
    const loginUrl = new URL("/account", req.url); // Redirect to your sign-in page
    loginUrl.searchParams.set("callbackUrl", req.nextUrl.href);
    return NextResponse.redirect(loginUrl);
  }

  return NextResponse.next();
}

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    "/((?!api|_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|images|assets).*)",
  ],
};
  2. Update /account/page.tsx (Conditional Rendering): Ensure your /account/page.tsx component uses the useSession() hook to determine if the user is authenticated.
    • If session.status === "unauthenticated" or !session.data, it should render your sign-in form.
    • If session.status === "authenticated", it should render the user's account dashboard/overview. You likely have this logic already, but it's good to confirm it aligns with /account being the primary landing/login page for the account section.
This approach resolves the redirect loop by allowing unauthenticated users to reach the /account page (which is your designated sign-in page) without the middleware intercepting and redirecting them again to the same page.
Please implement these changes. Once you've tested and confirmed this resolves the HTTP 431 error permanently, let me know! We can then confidently close this issue and move on to discussing the Service Provider directory.
I'll update our task list to reflect this final step for the HTTP 431 error resolution. Looking forward to your confirmation!

iTournary: Occasion-Centric Experience Platform - Requirements

iTournary: Occasion-Centric Experience Platform - Requirements

1. Overarching Strategic Vision

iTournary will transition from a direct booking platform to an Occasion-Based Experience Platform. The core value proposition will be to help users plan and organize entire experiences centered around specific occasions, connecting them with curated providers and offering interactive planning tools.
Key Pillars of the New Vision:
  1. Occasion-First Organization: The user journey begins with selecting an occasion type (e.g., wedding, corporate retreat, family reunion). This choice will shape the platform experience, content, and provider recommendations.
  2. Curated Provider Connections: Emphasis on connecting users with expert-vetted service providers tailored to each occasion type. Direct inquiry will be prioritized over instant booking for providers.
  3. Interactive Experience Design: Provide tools that enable users to visualize, plan, and coordinate multiple components and providers for their complete occasion/experience.
  4. Community Insights: Offer access to anonymized past experiences, advice, and learnings from others who have planned similar occasions (a future-phase consideration).

2. Immediate Development Adjustments & Priorities (Next Sprint Focus)

2.1. Modify Service Provider Directory

  • Occasion Type Categorization: Service providers must be classifiable by the occasion types they specialize in or are suitable for.
  • Enhanced Filtering: Search and filtering within the directory must prioritize occasion-specific criteria.
  • Profile Updates: Provider profiles should prominently display their expertise and experience related to specific occasions.
  • Emphasis on Direct Inquiry: The primary call to action for providers will be direct inquiry, rather than booking.

2.2. Design Structure for "Experience Planner" (Replacing Booking System)

  • Interactive Planning Interface: Conceptualize an interface organized by occasion type.
  • Focus on Complete Experiences: The tool should help users build out a full experience, not just book individual services.
  • Occasion-Specific Inquiry: Inquiry forms integrated into the planner should gather details relevant to the chosen occasion and potentially multiple providers.
  • Provider Coordination: The planner should facilitate the conceptual coordination of multiple providers for a single occasion.

2.3. Create OccasionType Sanity Schema & Taxonomy

  • Develop a new Sanity schema for OccasionTypes.
  • Define detailed attributes for each occasion type (e.g., typical services needed, planning considerations, budget ranges, common locations).
  • Establish an initial taxonomy of major occasion types.

3. Broader Changes & New Technical Requirements

3.1. Occasion-Centric Data Model

  • OccasionType Schema (Sanity): As defined above.
  • Linkages: Resorts and Service Providers (in Sanity) must be linkable to OccasionTypes.
  • Experience Schema (Sanity/MongoDB): A new schema to represent a user-planned experience. This will likely combine selected occasion(s), chosen providers, notes, checklists, and other planning artifacts. The choice of Sanity vs. MongoDB will depend on the dynamic interaction needs.

3.2. Enhanced Inquiry System

  • Sophisticated Inquiry Forms: Replace generic forms with dynamic, templated forms tailored to different occasion types and the Experience Planner.
  • Availability Checking (Future): Where possible, integrate with provider APIs for real-time or near real-time availability checks (a longer-term goal, not MVP for inquiry).
  • Inquiry Management Dashboard: A dashboard for users to track their inquiries and communications. (A provider-side or admin-side dashboard could be a future enhancement).

3.3. User Account Enhancements

  • "My Planned Experiences" Section: Users can save, view, and manage the experiences they are planning.
  • Planning Tools & Checklists: Integrate general and occasion-specific planning tools, checklists, and timelines within the user account and Experience Planner.
  • Provider Communication Tracking: A system to help users track their communications with various providers for a planned experience.

3.4. Develop Occasion Landing Pages

  • Dedicated Entry Points: Create unique landing pages for each major occasion type.
  • Content: These pages should include:
    • Planning guides relevant to the occasion.
    • Checklists and timelines.
    • Showcases of curated providers ideal for that occasion.
    • Success stories, examples, or case studies.

4. Phased Approach (High-Level)

  • Sprint 1 (Immediate Focus):
    1. OccasionType schema and taxonomy.
    2. Service Provider Directory enhancements (occasion categorization, filtering, profile updates).
    3. Initial design and structure for Experience Planning tools.
  • Subsequent Sprints/Phases:
    • Development of Occasion Landing Pages.
    • Full build-out of the Experience Planner UI and backend.
    • Implementation of the enhanced inquiry system.
    • User account enhancements for planned experiences.
    • (Later) Community insights features.

5. Key Departures from Previous Plan

  • The direct "Booking System" (availability checking, room selection, booking flow, confirmation for resorts) is deferred/replaced by the "Experience Planner" and an enhanced direct inquiry model.
  • Payment processing integration is no longer an immediate concern for the core platform functionality, as the focus shifts from transactions to connections and planning.
  • The data model becomes fundamentally occasion-centric, influencing all other features.
This document will serve as the basis for the revised development roadmap and detailed planning for each feature. Further elaboration will occur for each specific component (e.g., detailed fields for Experience schema, UI mockups for Experience Planner).
